In TypeScript, you can use type guards to safely assert the type of a value without executing the code that might change the type. Here’s an example to illustrate this:

```typescript
type KnownType = {
    someValue: number; // This is the type we KNOW will be the only type
}

type ValuedType = knownTypeAsInstanceof KnownType | unknownType;

// Example of trying to bind it to an instance with a non-known type
const valuedInstance: ValuedType = {
    someValue: 42;
};

// Example of trying to bind it to an instance with a known type
const knownInstance: ValuedType = {
    someValue: 42; // This will fail with a type error
};
```

In this example, `valuedInstance` will throw a TypeScript error because `someValue` is of type `number`, but `knownInstance` will simply be assigned the value `42`.

However, in your case, you are specifically stating that the type will only have one value. This means your type variable should always be assigned exactly one value of its type. Therefore, you can make the type guard more explicit to explicitly assert this behavior:

```typescript
type KnownTypeWithSingleValue = {
    someValue: number; // Explicitly declared to enforce exactly one value
};

type ValuedTypeWithSingleValue = KnownTypeWithSingleValue | unknownType;

// Example of trying to bind it to an instance with an exact match
const valutedInstance: ValuedTypeWithSingleValue = {
    someValue: 42; // This will succeed without a type error
};

// Example of trying to bind it to an instance with a non-exact match
const valuedInstanceWithNonSingleValue = {
    someValue: 42; // This will fail with a type error
};
```

With these type guards, you can enforce that the value of the `someValue` will always be of the type `number`, even in practice, by making sure that `someValue` is exactly `42`.

